litics and policies from a gendered perspective, despite the fact that New Labour have set themselves up to specifically address women's issues and attract women voters. This book fills that gap in an interesting and timely way. Women and New Labour will be a valuable addition to both feminist and mainstream scholarship in the social sciences, particularly in political science, social policy and economics. Instead of focusing on traditionally feminist areas of politics and policy (such as violent crime against women) the authors opt to focus on three case study areas of mainstream policy (economic policy, foreign policy and welfare policy) from a gendered perspective. The analytical framework provided by the editors yields generalisable insights that will outlast New Labour's third term.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aFeminismxPolitical aspectszGreat Britain. 0aWomenxGovernment policyzGreat Britain. 0aWomenxPolitical activityzGreat Britain. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aAnnesley, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnnesley, Claire, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBuchanan, Guro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoates, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurose, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElias, Juanita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerguson, Lucy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGains, Francesca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGains, Francesca, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 